         (0, 2, 2, 3, 4, 4) |    1 |        1 |         2 | YES!
         (0, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4) |    3 |        1 |         2 | YES!
         (0, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3) |    1 |        1 |         1 | no
         (1, 1, 1, 3, 4, 5) |    1 |        1 |         1 | no
         (1, 1, 1, 4, 4, 4) |    1 |        1 |         1 | no
         (1, 1, 2, 2, 4, 5) |    1 |        1 |         1 | no
         (1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 5) |    1 |        1 |         2 | YES!
         (1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 4) |    2 |        3 |         3 | no
         (1, 1, 3, 3, 3, 4) |    3 |        3 |         3 | no
         (1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 5) |    3 |        1 |         2 | YES!
         (1, 2, 2, 2, 4, 4) |    3 |        3 |         3 | no
         (1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4) |    6 |        5 |         5 | no
         (1, 2, 3, 3, 3, 3) |    2 |        3 |         4 | YES!
         (2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 5) |    1 |        1 |         1 | no
         (2, 2, 2, 2, 3, 4) |    2 |        3 |         4 | YES!
         (2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3) |    3 |        3 |         4 | YES!

  RESULT: Ternary carries MORE information than binary at n=6!
  This means the overlap WEIGHT (not just adjacency) distinguishes
  tournaments that have the same conflict graph Omega.

